STEP 6B: Partial Correlation (CRITICAL - Disentangle from Baseline)
======================================================================

Data merged: 100 participants with confidence, slopes, and baseline accuracy
Baseline accuracy range: [-0.988, 2.026]

--- Zero-Order Correlations (Spearman) ---
Confidence-Slope: rho = -0.6348, p = 0.000000
Baseline-Slope: rho = -0.9528, p = 0.000000
Confidence-Baseline: rho = 0.5940, p = 0.000000

--- PARTIAL CORRELATION (Controlling Baseline Accuracy) ---
Partial rho (Confidence-Slope | Baseline): -0.2818
95% CI: [-0.4539, -0.0893]
t(97) = -2.892, p = 0.004720

--- INTERPRETATION ---
Partial rho = -0.2818 REMAINS SIGNIFICANT (p = 0.004720)
→ Confidence has UNIQUE predictive value beyond baseline ability
→ Metacognitive monitoring adds information not captured by baseline performance
→ Confidence is not merely a proxy for baseline ability

--- Variance Partitioning ---
Total variance explained by Confidence: 40.3%
Unique variance (after controlling baseline): 7.9%
Shared variance (with baseline ability): 32.4%
Proportion unique: 19.7% of total

Saved: data/step06b_partial_correlation.csv

